Aragorn spent most of his time walking through the woods, and trying to get some calories.  Harry spent years practicing how to transfigure cups.  Cups!!  Snowden mostly sat behind a computer, typing.  Boring and Epic layers, at the same time.  I feel we all have those two layers. It's easy for us to get caught up in the boring or mundane - but what's the REAL story?

text: Just for the record the NSA or CIA or FBI or any of those corporate government bodies are actually watching civilians 247. Phones, msgs, emails, etc are all being tracked. Make no mistake about it. Why y'all think Smart phones are fitted with GPS tracking devices? So they can locate you when need be. Hell even HD TV's have built in camera's so you are being watched in your own home. I might sound like I'm some loopy new age theorist but have you ever considered the truth? The truth is every film or story or T.V. show is based on a real concept and the conception of this story is VERY REAL! They sugar coat it in a movie as entertainment and it only has a subtle effect on your subconcious. However realistically they are actually doing this behind closed doors. The phrase ''art imitatiing life'' could not be any more definitive or exemplified as it is here.

text: I strongly suggest watching Citizenfour before watching this movie. It's the Documentary that was ACTUALLY being filmed before, during and after the leaks while the journalists and documentarians involved were ACTUALLY doing it. The atmosphere in that Hong Kong hotel must have been bonkers when Snowden met the journalists for the first time and to watch their reactions to Snowden explaining the ins and outs of the NSA meta-data collection for the first time is sooo cool. You are there while it ACTUALLY unfolds so for when you go and see this Snowden bio pic you can take apart what's fiction and what's not. I, for one, am excited about this movie. The more the world knows about this story the better

text: Lol such a mis-leading trailer.  "The NSA is really tracking every cell phone in the world". There is the ability to track thousands upon thousands of devices yes, whether they're all looked at is an entirely different subject. And I don't believe they could for EVERY phone in the world at once, but they could track any phone they were specifically after.  This was typical of Snowden, which he should have know better - to act and portray that people sit there at a computer and watch you through your webcam, or browse through your emails etc... this doesn't happen. There isn't enough manpower to do such a task, yet alone it be worth paying for.   Why else does companies like Google collect data? To prioritize product search or customer satisfaction. Companies like the NSA track data, and then sub-categorize searches for words, tabbed cell phones for known criminals, searches for specific items, duration, repetition etc they're done so that they can filter out the bad guys from the average citizen. And, to the disgust of the many it seems, you can really only achieve that with mass collection of data, then sift through it with technology...not people.   In my opinion - he's a traitor. He said he wanted to help make a difference in the world, and he would have known that spying happens everywhere for security reasons, so why does he take this and run to Russia? At least man up to the fact you've betrayed your country, possibly at the risk of others as well. He lost all credibility when he scurried off to Russia so conveniently timed, it almost seems like he was a mole lol.

text: Watching that portion  where he's being vetted by the CIA under polygraph and he says "I want to help my country make a difference in the world" it makes me wonder if too much idealism might actually be a negative in an interview for a top secret position.  On the one hand, you want idealistic patriotic people who will diligently do their job and won't be easily corrupted by a foreign intelligence agency.  On the other hand, these are precisely the sort of people who might sincerely object to some practice and decide that their conscience demands that they go public.  If you hired somebody who honestly said, "This is a good job that pays well and I will follow the rules in order to keep my job" someone like that is more likely to follow the rules without a question and not do anything to endanger their job or to risk prison but that mercenary attitude might also make them more vulnerable to being paid off by a foreign intelligence agency.  My guess is that the NSA, CIA etc. is probably looking for people who are idealistic and motivated by the idea of public service but who have a weak sense of individualism and the idea that right and wrong are an individual judgement call.  Or if they weren't before, they are certainly aware of the paradox at work post Snowden.
